item.description:
arXiv:2503.22431v1 Announce Type: new Abstract: Right-handed neutrinos $
u_R$ play a crucial role in flavor-changing neutral-current processes with missing energy, such as $b	o s + \slashed{E} $ and $d	o s + \slashed{E} $, where Belle-II reports unexpectedly large branching fraction in $B	o K 
u  ar
u$ decays. Assuming $
u_R$ is the partner of the active neutrino $
u_L$ in the standard model, a Dirac-type neutrino framework emerges. We investigate a scenario of radiative Dirac neutrino mass generation in a scalar leptoquark (LQ) model with a global $U(1)_X$ symmetry to suppress Majorana mass, tree-level Dirac mass, and diquark couplings. The simplest LQ realization consists of two $S_1 = (3,1,-1/3)$ LQs with distinct $U(1)_X$ charges. A non-Casas-Ibarra parametrization is proposed to match neutrino data with fewer model parameters. Imposing current experimental constraints from meson mixing and lepton flavor-violating processes, we find that right-handed neutrino effects can significantly enhance $B	o K^{(*)} 
u ar{
u}$ and $K^+	o \pi^+ 
u ar{
u}$. Additionally, the model predicts excesses in $R_D$ from $B	o D	au ar{
u}$ that remain within $1\sigma$ of current experimental data.
